Given an integer N, write a program to check whether the number is an Armstrong number or not.
An Armstrong number of n digits is an integer such that the sum of its digits raised to the power n is equal to the number itself.
For example:
153 is an Armstrong number since 1³ + 5³ + 3³ = 153.
9474 is an Armstrong number since 9⁴ + 4⁴ + 7⁴ + 4⁴ = 9474
Input Format

A single integer N
Constraints

0 ≤ N ≤ 10⁹
Output Format

Print true if the number is an Armstrong number, otherwise print false.
Sample Input 0

153
Sample Output 0

true
Sample Input 1

123
Sample Output 1

false

import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Solution {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);
        int n=sc.nextInt();
        int temp=n;
        int digits=0;
        int copy=n;
        while(copy!=0){
            digits++;
            copy/=10;
        }
        int sum=0;
        copy=n;
        while(copy!=0){
            int digit=copy%10;
            sum+=Math.pow(digit,digits);
            copy/=10;
        }
        if(sum==temp){
            System.out.println("true");
        }else{
            System.out.println("false");
        }
    }
}
